-- ============================================================================
-- Quiz Seed: Matthew — Part 4 (Chapters 19–24)
-- 3 difficulties × 6 chapters = 96 total questions
--   kids:   3 per chapter  = 18
--   teens:  5 per chapter  = 30
--   adults: 8 per chapter  = 48
-- ============================================================================

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 19–21 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 19 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 19, 'kids', 1, 'What did Jesus say when the disciples tried to stop people from bringing children to Him?', 'Suffer little children, and forbid them not, to come unto me: for of such is the kingdom of heaven', 'Send the children away', 'Only adults may see me', 'Children should wait until they are older', 'a', 'Matthew 19:14 — "But Jesus said, Suffer little children, and forbid them not, to come unto me: for of such is the kingdom of heaven."'),
('Matthew', 19, 'kids', 2, 'What did the rich young man ask Jesus?', 'Good Master, what good thing shall I do, that I may have eternal life?', 'How can I become the king of Israel?', 'Where is the best place to build a house?', 'How can I make more money?', 'a', 'Matthew 19:16 — "And, behold, one came and said unto him, Good Master, what good thing shall I do, that I may have eternal life?"'),
('Matthew', 19, 'kids', 3, 'What animal did Jesus say was easier to go through the eye of a needle than a rich man entering God''s kingdom?', 'A camel', 'A horse', 'A donkey', 'An elephant', 'a', 'Matthew 19:24 — "It is easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle, than for a rich man to enter into the kingdom of God."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 19, 'teens', 1, 'What did Jesus teach about God''s original design for marriage?', 'God made them male and female from the beginning, and a man shall leave father and mother and cleave to his wife — they are no more twain but one flesh. What God hath joined together, let not man put asunder', 'Marriage is only a human tradition', 'Divorce is always acceptable for any reason', 'Marriage was invented by Moses', 'a', 'Matthew 19:4-6 — "Have ye not read, that he which made them at the beginning made them male and female... What therefore God hath joined together, let not man put asunder."'),
('Matthew', 19, 'teens', 2, 'Why did Moses allow divorce, according to Jesus?', 'Because of the hardness of their hearts — but from the beginning it was not so', 'Because God wanted people to divorce easily', 'Because marriage was not important in Moses'' time', 'Because women requested it', 'a', 'Matthew 19:8 — "He saith unto them, Moses because of the hardness of your hearts suffered you to put away your wives: but from the beginning it was not so."'),
('Matthew', 19, 'teens', 3, 'What did the rich young man do when Jesus told him to sell all he had and give to the poor?', 'He went away sorrowful, for he had great possessions', 'He immediately sold everything', 'He bargained for a lower amount', 'He asked for more time to decide', 'a', 'Matthew 19:22 — "But when the young man heard that saying, he went away sorrowful: for he had great possessions."'),
('Matthew', 19, 'teens', 4, 'What did Jesus promise the disciples who had left everything to follow Him?', 'In the regeneration, they would sit upon twelve thrones judging the twelve tribes of Israel — and everyone who has left houses, family, or lands for His sake shall receive a hundredfold and inherit everlasting life', 'They would receive nothing special', 'They would get their old jobs back', 'They would become wealthy immediately', 'a', 'Matthew 19:28-29 — "Ye which have followed me, in the regeneration when the Son of man shall sit in the throne of his glory, ye also shall sit upon twelve thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel."'),
('Matthew', 19, 'teens', 5, 'What surprising statement did Jesus make about who can be saved?', 'With men this is impossible; but with God all things are possible', 'Only rich people can be saved', 'Salvation is easy for everyone', 'No one can ever be saved', 'a', 'Matthew 19:26 — "But Jesus beheld them, and said unto them, With men this is impossible; but with God all things are possible."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 19, 'adults', 1, 'How does Jesus'' teaching on marriage (19:3-9) go beyond the Pharisees'' debate about acceptable grounds for divorce?', 'The Pharisees debated whether divorce was permitted for "any cause" (Hillel) or only for sexual immorality (Shammai). Jesus bypasses both schools by going back to creation (Genesis 1:27, 2:24) — establishing God''s original intent as the standard. Divorce was never God''s design but a concession to human sinfulness', 'Jesus sided with the school of Hillel', 'Jesus abolished marriage', 'The Pharisees never discussed divorce', 'a', 'Matthew 19:3-8 — The Pharisees ask about grounds for divorce; Jesus redirects to God''s design for marriage. By citing Genesis before Deuteronomy, He establishes creation-intent as normative: "from the beginning it was not so." Divorce is a concession to fallenness, not a component of the created order.'),
('Matthew', 19, 'adults', 2, 'What does the rich young ruler episode reveal about the relationship between wealth and salvation?', 'The young man''s attachment to wealth prevented him from following Jesus — his possessions possessed him. Jesus does not condemn wealth per se but exposes its idolatrous potential: when wealth becomes the thing you cannot surrender, it has become your god. The camel/needle metaphor shows that self-salvation through riches is humanly impossible', 'Wealthy people cannot be saved', 'Poverty guarantees salvation', 'Jesus approved of the young man''s choice', 'a', 'Matthew 19:21-24 — "If thou wilt be perfect, go and sell that thou hast... he went away sorrowful." The young man''s sorrow reveals his true master. The command was diagnostic: "sell all" exposed the idol. The camel/needle imagery means human impossibility — only divine grace can save the wealthy or anyone else (v.26).'),
('Matthew', 19, 'adults', 3, 'What does "with men this is impossible; but with God all things are possible" (19:26) teach about the nature of salvation?', 'Salvation is impossible through human effort, religious achievement, or moral reform — it requires a divine miracle. Even the disciples are "exceedingly amazed" (v.25), asking "Who then can be saved?" Jesus'' answer applies to everyone: no one can save themselves. Salvation is entirely God''s work of grace', 'Salvation is achievable through sufficient effort', 'Only the rich find it impossible', 'God makes it possible by lowering the standard', 'a', 'Matthew 19:25-26 — "Who then can be saved? ...With men this is impossible; but with God all things are possible." The disciples'' shock reveals that everyone assumed wealth was a sign of God''s favour. If the blessed-by-God rich cannot be saved by their advantages, no one can be saved by human means. Salvation is entirely a divine work.'),
('Matthew', 19, 'adults', 4, 'What does the "regeneration" (palingenesia) in 19:28 refer to?', 'The Greek "palingenesia" (literally "new birth/genesis again") refers to the cosmic renewal at Christ''s return — the new heavens and new earth (Isaiah 65:17; Revelation 21:1). In this renewed creation, the apostles will share in Christ''s rule, judging (governing/leading) the restored twelve tribes of Israel', 'It refers to personal conversion', 'It means the temple being rebuilt', 'It describes a political revolution', 'a', 'Matthew 19:28 — "In the regeneration when the Son of man shall sit in the throne of his glory." Palingenesia appears only here and in Titus 3:5 (personal regeneration). Here it is cosmic — the restoration of all things (Acts 3:21). The twelve thrones correspond to the twelve tribes, fulfilling Israel''s ultimate restoration.'),
('Matthew', 19, 'adults', 5, 'Why does Jesus initially respond "Why callest thou me good? there is none good but one, that is, God" (19:17)?', 'Jesus is not denying His goodness or deity but challenging the young man''s casual use of "good." Either "good" is a superficial compliment (in which case it is hollow) or it implies deity (in which case the young man should follow through on its implications). Jesus forces him to take his own words seriously', 'Jesus was denying His divinity', 'Jesus was being humble and nothing more', 'Jesus did not understand the question', 'a', 'Matthew 19:17 — "Why callest thou me good? there is none good but one, that is, God." Jesus does not say "I am not good" but asks "Why do you call me good?" The implied logic: if goodness belongs to God alone, and you rightly call me good, what does that say about who I am? The question is Christological, not a denial.'),
('Matthew', 19, 'adults', 6, 'What does "many that are first shall be last; and the last shall be first" (19:30) summarise?', 'The great reversal is a kingdom principle: those with worldly advantage (wealth, status, religious credentials) who refuse to follow Jesus will end up last, while those who sacrifice everything — the socially last — will be first. This principle reverses human merit systems and grounds kingdom status in grace and costly obedience, not in privilege', 'The chronologically first arrivals will be served last', 'This statement has no practical meaning', 'Only applies to the twelve apostles', 'a', 'Matthew 19:30 — "Many that are first shall be last; and the last shall be first." This aphorism bookends chapter 19-20 (repeated in 20:16), framing the rich young ruler''s failure (first → last) and the disciples'' sacrifice (last → first). The kingdom inverts every human ranking.'),
('Matthew', 19, 'adults', 7, 'How do Jesus'' words about eunuchs "for the kingdom of heaven''s sake" (19:12) relate to celibacy and calling?', 'Jesus acknowledges three categories: congenital eunuchs, those made eunuchs by others, and those who voluntarily embrace celibacy for the kingdom. This legitimises both marriage and celibacy as valid callings, with celibacy being a special gift ("he that is able to receive it, let him receive it") — not a superior state but a particular vocation', 'Jesus commanded all followers to be celibate', 'Only married people can serve God', 'This verse has no practical application', 'a', 'Matthew 19:12 — "There be eunuchs, which have made themselves eunuchs for the kingdom of heaven''s sake. He that is able to receive it, let him receive it." Jesus neither mandates celibacy nor devalues it. It is a gift (cf. 1 Corinthians 7:7) for those called to it, freeing them for undivided kingdom service.'),
('Matthew', 19, 'adults', 8, 'What does Jesus'' blessing of the children (19:13-15) teach about the nature of receiving the kingdom?', 'The kingdom belongs to those who come as children do — with empty hands, no achievements, no bargaining chips, and complete dependence. This stands in direct contrast to the rich young ruler who approaches with a "What good thing shall I do?" mindset. Children receive gifts; adults try to earn them. The kingdom is received, not achieved', 'Children are sinless and therefore worthy', 'Only literal children can enter the kingdom', 'The blessing was a social custom with no theology', 'a', 'Matthew 19:14 — "Of such is the kingdom of heaven." The juxtaposition with the rich young ruler (vv.16-22) is deliberate: children receive freely; the ruler wants to earn his way. The kingdom is a gift to the empty-handed (children), not a reward for the accomplished (the ruler).');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 20 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 20, 'kids', 1, 'In Jesus'' story about the workers in the vineyard, how much did every worker receive at the end of the day?', 'One penny (denarius) — even those who only worked for one hour received the same as those who worked all day', 'The early workers received much more', 'The late workers received nothing', 'Everyone received different amounts', 'a', 'Matthew 20:9-10 — "And when they came that were hired about the eleventh hour, they received every man a penny. But when the first came, they supposed that they should have received more; and they likewise received every man a penny."'),
('Matthew', 20, 'kids', 2, 'What did the mother of James and John ask Jesus?', 'She asked that her two sons might sit on Jesus'' right and left hand in His kingdom', 'She asked Jesus to heal her sons', 'She asked Jesus for money', 'She asked Jesus to visit her home', 'a', 'Matthew 20:21 — "She saith unto him, Grant that these my two sons may sit, the one on thy right hand, and the other on the left, in thy kingdom."'),
('Matthew', 20, 'kids', 3, 'What did Jesus say He came to do?', 'The Son of man came not to be ministered unto, but to minister, and to give his life a ransom for many', 'He came to be served by everyone', 'He came to become a wealthy ruler', 'He came to build a great palace', 'a', 'Matthew 20:28 — "Even as the Son of man came not to be ministered unto, but to minister, and to give his life a ransom for many."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 20, 'teens', 1, 'What lesson does the parable of the workers in the vineyard teach?', 'God''s generosity is not based on how long you''ve served — He gives the same grace to those who come late as to those who have been faithful since the beginning. "The last shall be first, and the first last"', 'You should always try to work the longest', 'God pays based on hours worked', 'Those who come first are always rewarded more', 'a', 'Matthew 20:1-16 — "So the last shall be first, and the first last: for many be called, but few chosen." The parable illustrates grace: God''s generosity does not follow human calculations of merit. The landowner''s response: "Is it not lawful for me to do what I will with mine own? Is thine eye evil, because I am good?"'),
('Matthew', 20, 'teens', 2, 'What "cup" did Jesus say James and John would drink?', 'The cup of suffering — they would indeed share in His suffering and persecution', 'A cup of celebration at a feast', 'A cup of wine at a wedding', 'A cup of water from the well', 'a', 'Matthew 20:22-23 — "Ye shall drink indeed of my cup, and be baptized with the baptism that I am baptized with: but to sit on my right hand, and on my left, is not mine to give, but it shall be given to them for whom it is prepared of my Father."'),
('Matthew', 20, 'teens', 3, 'How did Jesus define greatness for His disciples?', 'Whosoever will be great among you, let him be your minister (servant); and whosoever will be chief among you, let him be your servant', 'The greatest should be the most powerful', 'Greatness means having the most followers', 'The oldest disciple is automatically the greatest', 'a', 'Matthew 20:26-27 — "But it shall not be so among you: but whosoever will be great among you, let him be your minister; And whosoever will be chief among you, let him be your servant."'),
('Matthew', 20, 'teens', 4, 'What did the two blind men near Jericho cry out to Jesus?', 'Have mercy on us, O Lord, thou Son of David', 'Give us money for food', 'Tell us the way to Jerusalem', 'Make us your disciples', 'a', 'Matthew 20:30 — "And, behold, two blind men sitting by the way side, when they heard that Jesus passed by, cried out, saying, Have mercy on us, O Lord, thou Son of David."'),
('Matthew', 20, 'teens', 5, 'What did the third passion prediction add that the earlier ones did not?', 'It specifically mentions being delivered to the Gentiles, being mocked, scourged, and crucified — and rising again the third day', 'It removed the prediction of resurrection', 'It predicted Jesus becoming king instead', 'It said Jesus would escape death', 'a', 'Matthew 20:18-19 — "The Son of man shall be betrayed unto the chief priests and unto the scribes, and they shall condemn him to death, And shall deliver him to the Gentiles to mock, and to scourge, and to crucify him: and the third day he shall rise again."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 20, 'adults', 1, 'What does the parable of the vineyard workers teach about grace versus merit?', 'The parable attacks the principle that God rewards proportionally to human effort. The grumbling of the early workers exposes the transactional mindset ("we deserve more"). Grace is God''s sovereign generosity: "Is thine eye evil, because I am good?" Those offended by equal grace reveal that they serve for reward, not love', 'God is unfair to long-term workers', 'The parable teaches labour economics', 'Only the last-hired deserve reward', 'a', 'Matthew 20:15 — "Is it not lawful for me to do what I will with mine own? Is thine eye evil, because I am good?" The parable shatters merit-based religion. Grace is not unfair — it is generous. The "evil eye" (Jewish idiom for stinginess/envy) diagnoses the problem: they begrudge God''s goodness to others.'),
('Matthew', 20, 'adults', 2, 'How does Jesus'' "ransom" statement (20:28) establish the doctrine of substitutionary atonement?', 'The word "ransom" (lutron) means a price paid to liberate captives. "For" (anti) means "in the place of" — Jesus gives His life as a substitute for many. This single verse contains substitution (His life for ours), liberation (ransom from sin/death), and scope (many, not all, yet sufficient for all). It is the most concentrated atonement statement in Matthew', 'Jesus'' death was merely an example of sacrifice', 'Ransom implies God owed a payment to Satan', 'The verse does not address atonement', 'a', 'Matthew 20:28 — "To give his life a ransom (lutron) for (anti) many." Lutron (ransom price) + anti (in place of) = substitutionary atonement. Jesus'' life is the price that liberates "many" (cf. Isaiah 53:11-12 "shall my righteous servant justify many... he bare the sin of many").'),
('Matthew', 20, 'adults', 3, 'What does Jesus'' third passion prediction (20:17-19) reveal about His foreknowledge and willingness?', 'This is the most detailed prediction: betrayal, condemnation, delivery to Gentiles, mocking, scourging, and crucifixion — yet followed by resurrection. Jesus approaches His death with full knowledge and deliberate intention. He is not a victim but a willing sacrifice, predicting every detail because He is sovereignly walking into the Father''s plan', 'Jesus was guessing about what might happen', 'The prediction was added after the events', 'Jesus was uncertain about the outcome', 'a', 'Matthew 20:17-19 — The progression of detail: 1st prediction (16:21) = suffer, be killed, rise; 2nd (17:22-23) = betrayed, killed, rise; 3rd (20:18-19) = betrayed, condemned, delivered to Gentiles, mocked, scourged, crucified, rise. Each adds specificity, showing Jesus'' complete foreknowledge.'),
('Matthew', 20, 'adults', 4, 'How does the mother of Zebedee''s sons'' request (20:20-21) reveal persistent misunderstanding of Jesus'' kingdom?', 'Even after three passion predictions, the disciples (through James and John''s mother) still envision a political kingdom with positions of honour and power. The request exposes the gap between Jesus'' servant-kingdom and the disciples'' glory-kingdom. Jesus redirects: the path to thrones goes through suffering ("can ye drink of my cup?")', 'The request was perfectly appropriate', 'The mother was acting alone without her sons'' knowledge', 'Jesus had promised these specific positions', 'a', 'Matthew 20:20-22 — The request for right-hand and left-hand seats (positions of highest honour) comes immediately after the third passion prediction — showing the disciples heard "kingdom" but filtered out "suffering." Jesus responds with the cup metaphor: glory comes through suffering, not instead of it.'),
('Matthew', 20, 'adults', 5, 'What does "the Son of man came not to be ministered unto, but to minister" establish as the model for Christian leadership?', 'Jesus rejects the Gentile leadership model (authority as domination, v.25) and establishes servant leadership — where authority is exercised through service. The ultimate proof is His death: the highest authority (Son of man) performs the lowest service (giving His life). Christian leadership is measured by sacrifice, not by status', 'Christian leaders should seek power and honour', 'Servanthood is only for non-leaders', 'Jesus'' example applies only to Him', 'a', 'Matthew 20:25-28 — "It shall not be so among you" marks a categorical break from worldly power structures. Gentile rulers "exercise dominion" (katakurieuousin) and "exercise authority" (katexousiazousin) — both verbs suggest oppressive control. Jesus'' alternative: the greatest serves the most, following His own example of ransom-giving death.'),
('Matthew', 20, 'adults', 6, 'What is the "cup" Jesus refers to, and what does it signify in Old Testament imagery?', 'In the OT, "the cup" is a recurring metaphor for God''s wrath and judgment (Psalm 75:8; Isaiah 51:17,22; Jeremiah 25:15). Jesus'' cup is the cup of divine wrath against sin that He will drink on the cross in humanity''s place. James and John, in saying "we are able," do not grasp the full weight of what they agree to', 'The cup is a literal drinking vessel', 'The cup represents celebration and joy', 'The cup metaphor is unique to the New Testament', 'a', 'Matthew 20:22 — "Are ye able to drink of the cup that I shall drink of?" In Gethsemane (26:39), Jesus prays to have "this cup" removed. The cup = God''s wrath (Isaiah 51:17; Jeremiah 25:15-16). The disciples will indeed suffer (Acts 12:2, James martyred), but only Jesus drinks the cup of divine judgment in full.'),
('Matthew', 20, 'adults', 7, 'How does the healing of the two blind men (20:29-34) serve as a transitional passage to the Passion narrative?', 'The blind men see what the sighted disciples miss — they call Jesus "Son of David" (messianic title), persist despite being told to be quiet, and receive mercy. Their healed sight contrasts with the disciples'' spiritual blindness about Jesus'' suffering. They then "followed him" — becoming model disciples as Jesus enters Jerusalem for the final week', 'The healing has no connection to surrounding passages', 'The blind men represent the Pharisees', 'This is a duplicate of another healing story', 'a', 'Matthew 20:30-34 — The blind men''s faith-sight exposes the disciples'' faith-blindness. They confess "Son of David" (the Davidic Messiah) as Jesus heads to Jerusalem. Their healed following frames the Triumphal Entry: those who truly see Jesus follow Him, even toward the cross.'),
('Matthew', 20, 'adults', 8, 'What does "many be called, but few chosen" (20:16) mean in the parable''s context?', 'The "many called" are all who hear the gospel invitation (like all the workers hired throughout the day). The "few chosen" does not mean God arbitrarily selects some and rejects others, but that many who are called reject grace by insisting on merit-based reward (like the grumbling workers). The chosen are those who accept grace as grace, without demanding that God conform to their calculations', 'God only calls a few people', 'Everyone who is called is automatically chosen', 'This phrase applies to a different parable', 'a', 'Matthew 20:16 — "Many be called, but few chosen." In context, the "called" are all the workers; the "chosen" are those who accept the landowner''s generous terms. The first-hired workers are "called" but disqualify themselves by demanding merit-based payment. Grace accepted = chosen; grace resented = self-excluded.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 21 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 21, 'kids', 1, 'What animal did Jesus ride into Jerusalem on?', 'A donkey (and a colt, the foal of a donkey)', 'A horse', 'A camel', 'A chariot', 'a', 'Matthew 21:7 — "And brought the ass, and the colt, and put on them their clothes, and they set him thereon."'),
('Matthew', 21, 'kids', 2, 'What did the people shout as Jesus rode into Jerusalem?', 'Hosanna to the Son of David: Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord; Hosanna in the highest', 'Go away, we do not want you', 'Long live Caesar', 'Welcome to the marketplace', 'a', 'Matthew 21:9 — "And the multitudes that went before, and that followed, cried, saying, Hosanna to the Son of David: Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord; Hosanna in the highest."'),
('Matthew', 21, 'kids', 3, 'What did Jesus do when He found people buying and selling in the temple?', 'He overthrew the tables of the moneychangers and said "My house shall be called the house of prayer; but ye have made it a den of thieves"', 'He bought some things for Himself', 'He sat down and watched', 'He asked them to sell cheaper items', 'a', 'Matthew 21:12-13 — "And Jesus went into the temple of God, and cast out all them that sold and bought in the temple, and overthrew the tables of the moneychangers... My house shall be called the house of prayer; but ye have made it a den of thieves."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 21, 'teens', 1, 'What Old Testament prophecy did the Triumphal Entry fulfil?', 'Zechariah 9:9 — "Tell ye the daughter of Sion, Behold, thy King cometh unto thee, meek, and sitting upon an ass, and a colt the foal of an ass"', 'Isaiah 53 about the suffering servant', 'Daniel 7 about the Son of Man', 'Micah 5:2 about Bethlehem', 'a', 'Matthew 21:4-5 — "All this was done, that it might be fulfilled which was spoken by the prophet, saying, Tell ye the daughter of Sion, Behold, thy King cometh unto thee, meek, and sitting upon an ass, and a colt the foal of an ass."'),
('Matthew', 21, 'teens', 2, 'What happened to the fig tree Jesus cursed?', 'It withered away immediately — Jesus used it as a lesson about faith', 'It grew more leaves', 'It produced fruit the next day', 'Nothing happened at all', 'a', 'Matthew 21:19-20 — "And presently the fig tree withered away. And when the disciples saw it, they marvelled, saying, How soon is the fig tree withered away!"'),
('Matthew', 21, 'teens', 3, 'In the parable of the two sons, which son did the will of the father?', 'The first son who initially said "I will not" but afterward repented and went — representing tax collectors and sinners who initially disobeyed God but later repented', 'The second son who said "I go, sir" but did not actually go', 'Both sons did the father''s will equally', 'Neither son obeyed the father', 'a', 'Matthew 21:29-31 — "He answered and said, I will not: but afterward he repented, and went... Whether of them twain did the will of his father? They say unto him, The first."'),
('Matthew', 21, 'teens', 4, 'What is the parable of the wicked husbandmen about?', 'God (the landowner) sent prophets (servants) to Israel (the vineyard), but the leaders (husbandmen) rejected and killed them. Finally He sent His Son (Jesus), whom they also killed. The kingdom would be taken from them and given to others', 'A lesson about good farming practices', 'A story about paying fair wages', 'A tale about building a vineyard', 'a', 'Matthew 21:33-43 — "He sent unto them his servants... they beat one, and killed another... Last of all he sent unto them his son... They caught him, and cast him out of the vineyard, and slew him... The kingdom of God shall be taken from you, and given to a nation bringing forth the fruits thereof."'),
('Matthew', 21, 'teens', 5, 'What did Jesus say about faith and prayer in connection with the fig tree?', 'If ye have faith, and doubt not, ye shall not only do this which is done to the fig tree, but also if ye shall say unto this mountain, Be thou removed, and be thou cast into the sea; it shall be done', 'Faith has nothing to do with prayer', 'Only special people can pray with power', 'Prayer works without any faith', 'a', 'Matthew 21:21 — "If ye have faith, and doubt not, ye shall not only do this which is done to the fig tree, but also if ye shall say unto this mountain, Be thou removed, and be thou cast into the sea; it shall be done."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 21, 'adults', 1, 'Why does Jesus ride a donkey rather than a horse into Jerusalem?', 'A horse was the animal of war (Revelation 19:11); a donkey was the animal of peace (Judges 5:10, kings rode donkeys in peacetime). By choosing a donkey, Jesus fulfils Zechariah 9:9 and declares Himself a peaceful king — claiming royal authority while rejecting military conquest. He enters as the Prince of Peace, not a warrior', 'Donkeys were more expensive than horses', 'Jesus could not find a horse', 'Riding a donkey was shameful and Jesus was being humble', 'a', 'Matthew 21:5 — "Thy King cometh unto thee, meek, and sitting upon an ass." Zechariah 9:9 describes a king who is "just, and having salvation; lowly" — the opposite of a conquering general on a warhorse. Jesus'' choice of mount is a theological statement about the nature of His kingdom.'),
('Matthew', 21, 'adults', 2, 'What does the temple cleansing (21:12-13) reveal about Jesus'' authority and the state of worship?', 'By cleansing the temple, Jesus acts with prophetic authority (cf. Malachi 3:1-3, "the Lord... shall suddenly come to his temple"). The Court of the Gentiles had become a marketplace, preventing Gentile worship. Jesus'' quotation combines Isaiah 56:7 ("house of prayer for all nations") with Jeremiah 7:11 ("den of robbers"), accusing the leaders of converting worship space into commerce', 'Jesus objected to all commerce', 'The temple cleansing was a minor incident', 'Only the Romans were selling in the temple', 'a', 'Matthew 21:12-13 — "My house shall be called the house of prayer; but ye have made it a den of thieves." Isaiah 56:7 includes "for all people" — the Gentile court was being misused. Jeremiah 7:11''s "den of robbers" implies they used the temple as a hideout between acts of injustice. Jesus attacks both the commercial corruption and the exclusion of Gentiles.'),
('Matthew', 21, 'adults', 3, 'What does the cursing of the fig tree symbolise?', 'The fig tree represents Israel: outward appearance of vitality (leaves) but no fruit (deeds of righteousness). Jesus'' cursing enacts a prophetic judgment on fruitless religion — specifically the temple establishment that looked religious but bore no spiritual fruit. The withering demonstrates that God judges appearance without substance', 'Jesus was merely hungry and disappointed', 'The fig tree represents Rome', 'It was a random act of power', 'a', 'Matthew 21:19 — "And when he saw a fig tree in the way, he came to it, and found nothing thereon, but leaves only." The fig tree is a common OT symbol for Israel (Jeremiah 8:13, Hosea 9:10, Micah 7:1). Leaves without fruit = outward religion without genuine righteousness. The temple cleansing (vv.12-13) and fig tree (vv.18-19) interpret each other.'),
('Matthew', 21, 'adults', 4, 'How does the parable of the two sons (21:28-32) trap the religious leaders?', 'The Pharisees identify the first son (who initially refused but later obeyed) as doing the father''s will — then Jesus applies it: tax collectors and harlots who initially lived in disobedience but repented enter the kingdom, while religious leaders who said "I go, sir" (outward compliance) but never truly obeyed are shut out', 'The Pharisees refused to answer', 'The parable was too complex to understand', 'Jesus praised both sons equally', 'a', 'Matthew 21:31 — "Verily I say unto you, That the publicans and the harlots go into the kingdom of God before you." The trap: the Pharisees correctly identify the obedient son, then discover they are the disobedient one. Their verbal religion ("I go, sir") without actual repentance is worse than initial refusal followed by genuine change.'),
('Matthew', 21, 'adults', 5, 'What does the parable of the wicked husbandmen (21:33-46) predict about Israel''s leadership and the kingdom''s transfer?', 'The parable allegorically traces Israel''s rejection of the prophets (servants) and the coming murder of the Son (Jesus). "The kingdom of God shall be taken from you, and given to a nation bringing forth the fruits thereof" predicts the transfer of kingdom responsibility from Israel''s leaders to the church (a "nation" from every nation, 1 Peter 2:9)', 'The kingdom remains with the same leaders', 'The vineyard represents Rome', 'The son in the parable represents John the Baptist', 'a', 'Matthew 21:43 — "The kingdom of God shall be taken from you, and given to a nation bringing forth the fruits thereof." The vineyard = Israel (Isaiah 5:1-7). The husbandmen = leaders. The servants = prophets. The son = Jesus. The "nation" (ethnos) = the church, a fruit-bearing people drawn from all nations (1 Peter 2:9).'),
('Matthew', 21, 'adults', 6, 'How does the stone rejected by the builders (Psalm 118:22-23) connect the two parables in chapter 21?', 'The rejected stone links the wicked husbandmen parable (they kill the son) to the cornerstone imagery — the very stone Israel''s leaders reject becomes the foundation of God''s new building. Those who "fall on this stone" (stumble over Christ in this life) will be broken in repentance; those on whom it "falls" (in judgment) will be crushed', 'The stone has no messianic significance', 'Only the parable of the husbandmen matters', 'The stone represents the temple building', 'a', 'Matthew 21:42-44 — "The stone which the builders rejected, the same is become the head of the corner." Psalm 118:22 was sung at Passover — Jesus quotes it during Passover week. The "builders" (Israel''s leaders) rejected Jesus, but God made Him the cornerstone. The stone imagery adds judicial consequences to the parable''s warning.'),
('Matthew', 21, 'adults', 7, 'What does "Hosanna to the Son of David" reveal about the crowd''s expectations?', '"Hosanna" means "save now" (from Psalm 118:25-26, a Passover psalm). "Son of David" is the messianic title. The crowd hails Jesus as the Davidic Messiah who will deliver Israel — but their expectations are political liberation, not spiritual salvation. The same crowd will shout "Crucify him" when Jesus fails to meet their political expectations', 'Hosanna was a common greeting with no significance', 'The crowd fully understood Jesus'' mission', 'Son of David was not a messianic title', 'a', 'Matthew 21:9 — "Hosanna to the Son of David." Psalm 118:25-26 was sung during the Feast of Tabernacles while waving palm branches. The crowd applies it to Jesus as the coming Davidic king. Their acclamation is theologically correct but their understanding is politically motivated — they want a liberator, not a lamb.'),
('Matthew', 21, 'adults', 8, 'How does Jesus'' authority question (21:23-27) about John''s baptism expose the leaders'' bad faith?', 'Jesus answers their question about His authority with a counter-question about John''s baptism (from heaven or from men?). The leaders cannot answer: affirming John means accepting Jesus (John testified to Jesus); denying John means angering the people (who revered John as a prophet). Their answer "We cannot tell" is not ignorance but dishonesty — they know but refuse to say. Jesus refuses to engage with bad faith', 'The leaders genuinely did not know the answer', 'Jesus was evading their question', 'John''s baptism was irrelevant to Jesus'' authority', 'a', 'Matthew 21:25-27 — "The baptism of John, whence was it? from heaven, or of men?" Their internal reasoning reveals calculated dishonesty: they reason politically, not truthfully. Jesus'' refusal to answer ("Neither tell I you") is not evasion but a refusal to cast pearls before swine (7:6) — truth requires honest interlocutors.');

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 22–24 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 22 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 22, 'kids', 1, 'In the parable of the wedding feast, who was invited when the original guests refused to come?', 'Everyone they could find — both bad and good — from the highways and hedges', 'Only the richest people in the city', 'Only the friends of the king', 'Nobody else was invited', 'a', 'Matthew 22:9-10 — "Go ye therefore into the highways, and as many as ye shall find, bid to the marriage. So those servants went out into the highways, and gathered together all as many as they found, both bad and good."'),
('Matthew', 22, 'kids', 2, 'What did Jesus say is the greatest commandment?', 'Thou shalt love the Lord thy God with all thy heart, and with all thy soul, and with all thy mind', 'Thou shalt not steal', 'Thou shalt keep the Sabbath', 'Thou shalt honour thy father and mother', 'a', 'Matthew 22:37 — "Jesus said unto him, Thou shalt love the Lord thy God with all thy heart, and with all thy soul, and with all thy mind."'),
('Matthew', 22, 'kids', 3, 'What is the second greatest commandment?', 'Thou shalt love thy neighbour as thyself', 'Thou shalt not lie', 'Thou shalt pray every day', 'Thou shalt go to the temple weekly', 'a', 'Matthew 22:39 — "And the second is like unto it, Thou shalt love thy neighbour as thyself."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 22, 'teens', 1, 'What happened to the man at the wedding feast who had no wedding garment?', 'The king said "Bind him hand and foot, and take him away, and cast him into outer darkness" — having no proper garment represents rejecting God''s provision of righteousness', 'The king gave him a new garment', 'Nothing happened, he stayed at the feast', 'He was asked to sit at a different table', 'a', 'Matthew 22:13 — "Then said the king to the servants, Bind him hand and foot, and take him away, and cast him into outer darkness; there shall be weeping and gnashing of teeth."'),
('Matthew', 22, 'teens', 2, 'How did Jesus answer the Pharisees'' trick question about paying taxes to Caesar?', 'Render therefore unto Caesar the things which are Caesar''s; and unto God the things that are God''s', 'Never pay taxes to Caesar', 'Pay everything to Caesar and nothing to God', 'Ignore the question entirely', 'a', 'Matthew 22:21 — "They say unto him, Caesar''s. Then saith he unto them, Render therefore unto Caesar the things which are Caesar''s; and unto God the things that are God''s."'),
('Matthew', 22, 'teens', 3, 'How did Jesus answer the Sadducees'' trick question about marriage and the resurrection?', 'In the resurrection they neither marry nor are given in marriage, but are as the angels of God in heaven. And God said "I am the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob" — He is not the God of the dead but of the living', 'Marriage continues exactly the same in heaven', 'There is no resurrection at all', 'Only the last husband counts', 'a', 'Matthew 22:30-32 — "For in the resurrection they neither marry, nor are given in marriage, but are as the angels of God in heaven... God is not the God of the dead, but of the living."'),
('Matthew', 22, 'teens', 4, 'On what two commandments did Jesus say all the law and the prophets hang?', 'Love God with all your heart, soul, and mind; and love your neighbour as yourself', 'Keep the Sabbath and honour your parents', 'Do not steal and do not lie', 'Pray daily and give to the temple', 'a', 'Matthew 22:40 — "On these two commandments hang all the law and the prophets."'),
('Matthew', 22, 'teens', 5, 'What unanswerable question did Jesus ask the Pharisees about the Messiah?', 'If David calls the Messiah "Lord" (in Psalm 110:1), how can the Messiah be merely David''s son? The Messiah must be greater than David — both his descendant and his Lord', 'He asked them about Roman tax policy', 'He asked them about the temple sacrifices', 'He asked them about Noah''s ark', 'a', 'Matthew 22:43-45 — "How then doth David in spirit call him Lord, saying, The LORD said unto my Lord, Sit thou on my right hand... If David then call him Lord, how is he his son?"'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 22, 'adults', 1, 'What does the man without a wedding garment represent in the parable of the wedding feast?', 'The wedding garment represents the righteousness God provides for entrance into His kingdom. The man who enters without it represents those who respond to the gospel invitation but refuse to accept God''s terms — coming on their own merits rather than clothed in Christ''s righteousness (cf. Isaiah 61:10, "garments of salvation," "robe of righteousness")', 'He represents a gate-crasher with no invitation', 'The garment represents physical clothing', 'He represents someone who arrived too early', 'a', 'Matthew 22:11-13 — "When the king came in... he saw there a man which had not on a wedding garment." In the ancient Near East, kings sometimes provided garments for guests (cf. Genesis 45:22). Refusing to wear the provided garment insults the host. The garment = imputed righteousness (Galatians 3:27, "put on Christ").'),
('Matthew', 22, 'adults', 2, 'How does "Render unto Caesar... and unto God" establish the relationship between church and state?', 'Jesus avoids both zealotism (refuse all taxes) and total submission (Caesar is God). By distinguishing Caesar''s legitimate claims (civil taxes) from God''s ultimate claims (the whole person, bearing God''s image), He establishes two overlapping but distinct spheres of obligation. The coin bears Caesar''s image; humans bear God''s image — and must be rendered to God completely', 'Christians should have no involvement in government', 'The state and God have equal claims', 'This was a political statement supporting Rome', 'a', 'Matthew 22:21 — "Render therefore unto Caesar... and unto God the things that are God''s." The deeper implication: coins bearing Caesar''s image belong to Caesar; humans bearing God''s image (Genesis 1:27) belong to God. Caesar gets taxes; God gets everything. The two spheres are asymmetric: God''s claim encompasses all of life.'),
('Matthew', 22, 'adults', 3, 'How does Jesus'' resurrection argument from Exodus 3:6 work logically?', 'God says "I AM (present tense) the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob" — not "I WAS." If these patriarchs ceased to exist at death, God would be the God of nothing. Since He is the God of the living, the patriarchs must still exist, implying resurrection. Jesus argues from a text the Sadducees accepted (Pentateuch) using grammar to prove resurrection', 'The argument is purely about grammar', 'The Sadducees already believed in resurrection', 'The present tense is insignificant', 'a', 'Matthew 22:31-32 — "I am the God of Abraham, and the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob? God is not the God of the dead, but of the living." The argument is brilliant: (1) God identifies Himself as their God in present tense; (2) God is God of the living; (3) therefore they must be alive; (4) therefore resurrection is real. QED.'),
('Matthew', 22, 'adults', 4, 'What does the double love command (22:37-40) teach about the unity of the Law?', 'All 613 commandments can be traced to these two: love God (vertical, first table of the Decalogue) and love neighbour (horizontal, second table). These two are not alternatives but inseparable — "the second is like unto it" means love of neighbour is the practical expression of love for God (cf. 1 John 4:20). The entire moral law is a commentary on love', 'The two commandments sometimes conflict', 'Only the first commandment matters', 'The second replaces the first', 'a', 'Matthew 22:37-40 — "On these two commandments hang all the law and the prophets." "Hang" (kremannumi) means the entire OT ethical structure depends on these two pegs. Love of God (Deuteronomy 6:5) and love of neighbour (Leviticus 19:18) together summarise all divine requirements.'),
('Matthew', 22, 'adults', 5, 'How does Jesus'' question about Psalm 110:1 challenge inadequate Christology?', 'If the Messiah is merely David''s human descendant, David would not call him "Lord." But David, inspired by the Spirit, calls the Messiah "my Lord" — implying the Messiah is more than human. The question forces acknowledgment that the Messiah is both David''s son (human descent) and David''s Lord (divine nature)', 'Jesus denies being David''s descendant', 'Psalm 110 is not about the Messiah', 'David did not write Psalm 110', 'a', 'Matthew 22:41-46 — "If David then call him Lord, how is he his son?" The Pharisees expected a human Messiah (David''s son). Jesus uses their own Scripture to show the Messiah must be more: David''s Lord who sits at God''s right hand. The answer: He is both — human (son) and divine (Lord).'),
('Matthew', 22, 'adults', 6, 'What does the progression of three hostile questions (taxes, resurrection, greatest commandment) reveal about Jesus'' opponents?', 'Pharisees, Herodians, and Sadducees — normally enemies — unite against Jesus (cf. Psalm 2:2, "rulers take counsel together, against the LORD, and against his anointed"). Each group attacks from their specialty: politics (taxes), theology (resurrection), and ethics (greatest command). Jesus defeats all three, silencing them permanently (v.46)', 'The questioners were genuinely curious', 'Only one group opposed Jesus', 'Jesus refused to answer any questions', 'a', 'Matthew 22:15-46 — Three hostile interrogations: (1) Pharisees + Herodians on taxes (vv.15-22); (2) Sadducees on resurrection (vv.23-33); (3) Pharisees on the Law (vv.34-40). After Jesus'' counter-question (vv.41-46), "no man was able to answer him a word, neither durst any man from that day forth ask him any more questions."'),
('Matthew', 22, 'adults', 7, 'What does the parable of the wedding feast (22:1-14) teach about the scope and conditions of the gospel invitation?', 'The parable shows three stages: (1) Israel''s leaders reject the invitation (vv.3-6); (2) the invitation extends to "both bad and good" — the universal gospel call (vv.9-10); (3) even among respondents, some are expelled for lacking the wedding garment (vv.11-13). The gospel is free but not cheap: invitation is universal, but entrance requires accepting God''s provision', 'Only pre-selected guests can attend', 'Everyone who enters automatically stays', 'The feast represents an earthly celebration', 'a', 'Matthew 22:1-14 — The parable expands the vineyard parable (21:33-46): rejection → judgment → transfer to others. The universality ("both bad and good") shows grace reaching all. The garment-check shows grace is not licence — response must include acceptance of God''s righteousness, not just showing up.'),
('Matthew', 22, 'adults', 8, 'What does "many are called, but few are chosen" (22:14) mean in the wedding feast context?', 'The invitation goes out broadly ("many called" — both the original invitees and the highway gatherers), but not all who respond genuinely enter the kingdom ("few chosen"). Being "called" means receiving the invitation; being "chosen" means having the proper wedding garment — genuine faith that accepts God''s provision of righteousness, not self-righteousness', 'God secretly predetermines who is chosen regardless of response', 'Everyone who shows up is automatically chosen', 'Called and chosen are identical concepts', 'a', 'Matthew 22:14 — In context, "called" = invited (all who hear the gospel); "chosen" = those who properly respond (wearing the garment). The man without the garment was called but not chosen — he responded outwardly but rejected God''s terms. Election and responsibility are held together.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 23 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 23, 'kids', 1, 'What did Jesus call the scribes and Pharisees because they pretended to be good but weren''t?', 'Hypocrites — like whitewashed tombs that look beautiful outside but are full of dead men''s bones inside', 'Heroes', 'Saints', 'Brave soldiers', 'a', 'Matthew 23:27 — "Woe unto you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! for ye are like unto whited sepulchres, which indeed appear beautiful outward, but are within full of dead men''s bones, and of all uncleanness."'),
('Matthew', 23, 'kids', 2, 'What did Jesus say about the Pharisees and heavy burdens?', 'They tie up heavy burdens and put them on people''s shoulders, but they themselves will not move them with one of their fingers', 'They carry everyone''s burdens happily', 'They make burdens lighter for everyone', 'They never give anyone any rules', 'a', 'Matthew 23:4 — "For they bind heavy burdens and grievous to be borne, and lay them on men''s shoulders; but they themselves will not move them with one of their fingers."'),
('Matthew', 23, 'kids', 3, 'How did Jesus feel about Jerusalem at the end of this chapter?', 'He wished He could have gathered her children together like a hen gathers her chicks under her wings, but they would not come', 'He was angry and wanted to punish them', 'He did not care about the city anymore', 'He was happy to leave them alone', 'a', 'Matthew 23:37 — "O Jerusalem, Jerusalem... how often would I have gathered thy children together, even as a hen gathereth her chickens under her wings, and ye would not!"'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 23, 'teens', 1, 'How many "woes" did Jesus pronounce on the scribes and Pharisees?', 'Seven woes — each one exposing a different form of hypocrisy', 'Three woes', 'Ten woes', 'One woe', 'a', 'Matthew 23:13-29 — Jesus pronounces seven woes: (1) shutting up the kingdom (v.13), (2) making converts twice the children of hell (v.15), (3) blind guides with oaths (v.16), (4) tithing herbs but neglecting justice (v.23), (5) cleaning the outside of the cup (v.25), (6) whitewashed tombs (v.27), (7) building prophets'' tombs while plotting murder (v.29).'),
('Matthew', 23, 'teens', 2, 'What did Jesus accuse the Pharisees of tithing while neglecting more important things?', 'They tithed mint, anise, and cummin (tiny herbs) but neglected the weightier matters of the law: judgment, mercy, and faith', 'They tithed their land but neglected their families', 'They tithed their animals but neglected worship', 'They tithed their time but neglected prayer', 'a', 'Matthew 23:23 — "Woe unto you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! for ye pay tithe of mint and anise and cummin, and have omitted the weightier matters of the law, judgment, mercy, and faith: these ought ye to have done, and not to leave the other undone."'),
('Matthew', 23, 'teens', 3, 'What did Jesus compare the Pharisees to in verse 24?', 'Blind guides that strain at a gnat and swallow a camel — meticulously filtering tiny impurities while ignoring massive sins', 'Wise scholars who know everything', 'Careful farmers who tend every plant', 'Strong builders who check every brick', 'a', 'Matthew 23:24 — "Ye blind guides, which strain at a gnat, and swallow a camel."'),
('Matthew', 23, 'teens', 4, 'What did Jesus say about the Pharisees making their phylacteries and fringes?', 'They made them broad and enlarged to be seen of men — all their works were done to be noticed by people, not to please God', 'They made them small and hidden', 'They threw them away as unnecessary', 'They shared them with the poor', 'a', 'Matthew 23:5 — "But all their works they do for to be seen of men: they make broad their phylacteries, and enlarge the borders of their garments."'),
('Matthew', 23, 'teens', 5, 'What prophecy did Jesus make about the temple at the end of chapter 23?', 'Behold, your house is left unto you desolate — the temple and Jerusalem would be abandoned by God', 'The temple would stand forever', 'God would make the temple even bigger', 'The temple would be filled with gold', 'a', 'Matthew 23:38 — "Behold, your house is left unto you desolate."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 23, 'adults', 1, 'How do the seven woes function as a prophetic lawsuit against Israel''s leadership?', 'The seven woes mirror OT prophetic judgment oracles (cf. Isaiah 5:8-23, Habakkuk 2:6-19). Each "woe" (ouai) is a pronouncement of grief and judgment. Together they form a comprehensive indictment: the leaders obstruct salvation (v.13), corrupt converts (v.15), pervert ethics (vv.16-22), invert priorities (vv.23-24), practice external religion (vv.25-28), and murder prophets (vv.29-36)', 'The woes are mild suggestions for improvement', 'Jesus was merely venting frustration', 'The woes apply only to first-century Pharisees', 'a', 'Matthew 23:13-36 — The seven woes escalate from obstructing the kingdom to killing the prophets. The number seven (completeness) suggests a comprehensive, total indictment. The climax (vv.34-36) predicts continued persecution and declares that "all the righteous blood" will fall on "this generation."'),
('Matthew', 23, 'adults', 2, 'What does "ye compass sea and land to make one proselyte, and when he is made, ye make him twofold more the child of hell" mean?', 'The Pharisees'' missionary zeal was energetic but destructive — they converted Gentiles to a legalistic, merit-based religion that actually moved people further from God. Religious zeal without gospel truth produces converts worse off than before, because they adopt self-righteousness with even more fervour than their teachers', 'The Pharisees were excellent missionaries', 'Proselytes were always blessed by conversion', 'Jesus opposed all evangelism', 'a', 'Matthew 23:15 — "Twofold more the child of hell" (huios geennes) — the convert becomes doubly zealous for a corrupt system. Misguided religious zeal does not merely fail to save — it actively damns, because it provides the illusion of righteousness while the heart remains far from God.'),
('Matthew', 23, 'adults', 3, 'What does Jesus'' distinction between "weightier" and "lighter" matters of the law (23:23) teach about ethical priorities?', 'Not all commandments carry equal moral weight — justice, mercy, and faith are "weightier" (barutera) than tithing herbs. Jesus does not abolish tithing ("these ought ye to have done") but insists on proper priority: major ethical obligations must not be neglected for minor ritual ones. This hierarchy of values prevents legalistic distortion', 'All laws are exactly equal in importance', 'Jesus abolished tithing entirely', 'Minor laws can replace major ones', 'a', 'Matthew 23:23 — "The weightier matters of the law, judgment, mercy, and faith: these ought ye to have done, and not to leave the other undone." Jesus affirms both tiers but demands priority. The Pharisees inverted the hierarchy: meticulously tithing garden herbs while ignoring justice, mercy, and faithfulness.'),
('Matthew', 23, 'adults', 4, 'What does the hen/chicks metaphor (23:37) reveal about divine compassion and human resistance?', 'Jesus uses a maternal image — a hen protectively gathering chicks — to express God''s tender, persistent desire to protect and save Jerusalem. "I would... ye would not" holds together divine initiative and human rejection. God''s willingness to save was genuine; Israel''s refusal was voluntary. The tragedy is that human obstinacy can resist divine compassion', 'Jesus was indifferent to Jerusalem''s fate', 'God''s will can always be overridden', 'The hen represents Rome', 'a', 'Matthew 23:37 — "How often would I have gathered thy children together, even as a hen gathereth her chickens under her wings, and ye would not!" The repetition "O Jerusalem, Jerusalem" expresses deep grief. The "how often" implies multiple rejected overtures. The tension between divine willingness ("I would") and human resistance ("ye would not") is the Bible''s central tragedy.'),
('Matthew', 23, 'adults', 5, 'What does "your house is left unto you desolate" (23:38) signify about the temple?', 'God''s presence is departing from the temple — "your house" (not "my house") signals God''s disowning of the institution. This echoes Ezekiel 10-11 where God''s glory departed from the first temple before Babylon destroyed it. The second temple will face the same fate (AD 70) because God''s presence has now transferred to the true temple — Christ Himself', 'God will always dwell in the temple', 'The temple was never important to God', 'Jesus was speaking about a different house', 'a', 'Matthew 23:38 — The shift from "my house" (21:13) to "your house" (23:38) is devastating. God''s presence has vacated the temple. Ezekiel''s departure of the Shekinah (Ezekiel 10:18-19, 11:22-23) is replayed: the glory leaves before the judgment falls. Christ Himself is now the temple (John 2:19-21).'),
('Matthew', 23, 'adults', 6, 'How does Jesus'' command to do what the scribes and Pharisees say but not what they do (23:2-3) navigate authority and hypocrisy?', 'Jesus acknowledges the Pharisees'' legitimate teaching office ("Moses'' seat") while condemning their personal hypocrisy. This distinguishes the office from the officer: the truth of their teaching (insofar as they faithfully represent Moses) is valid even when their lives contradict it. Authority resides in the role and the Scripture, not in the moral perfection of the teacher', 'Everything the Pharisees taught was wrong', 'Hypocritical teachers cannot teach truth', 'Jesus endorsed all Pharisaic practices', 'a', 'Matthew 23:2-3 — "The scribes and the Pharisees sit in Moses'' seat: All therefore whatsoever they bid you observe, that observe and do; but do not ye after their works." Jesus separates the office (legitimate) from the conduct (hypocritical). Truth is truth regardless of the messenger''s character — but hypocrisy invalidates the messenger''s credibility.'),
('Matthew', 23, 'adults', 7, 'What is the significance of Jesus'' reference to "from the blood of righteous Abel unto the blood of Zacharias" (23:35)?', 'Abel (Genesis 4) is the first martyr and Zechariah son of Barachias (2 Chronicles 24:20-21) is the last in the Hebrew Bible''s canonical order (Chronicles is the last book in the Hebrew canon). Jesus spans the entire Old Testament — from first to last martyr — declaring that this generation bears responsibility for all of Israel''s prophet-killing history', 'Abel and Zechariah died on the same day', 'Jesus was listing two random names', 'These were the only two martyrs in the OT', 'a', 'Matthew 23:35 — "From the blood of righteous Abel unto the blood of Zacharias." In the Hebrew Bible, Genesis is first and Chronicles is last. Abel (first book''s martyr) to Zechariah (last book''s martyr) = the entire canonical span. Jesus declares that the current generation climaxes the whole history of prophet-rejection.'),
('Matthew', 23, 'adults', 8, 'How does chapter 23 function within the five-discourse structure of Matthew?', 'Chapter 23 begins the fifth and final discourse (chapters 23-25): the Eschatological Discourse. Chapter 23 pronounces judgment on the present; chapter 24 describes the coming destruction and end times; chapter 25 presents parables of readiness. The shift from woes (23) to prophecy (24-25) mirrors the OT pattern of prophetic judgment followed by eschatological vision', 'Chapter 23 is an independent section', 'It belongs to the fourth discourse', 'There are only three discourses in Matthew', 'a', 'Matthew 23-25 — The fifth discourse moves from judgment on the present generation (ch. 23, seven woes) to the future (ch. 24, Olivet Discourse) to readiness parables (ch. 25, virgins/talents/sheep-goats). This discourse parallels Moses'' final blessings and curses (Deuteronomy 27-30), with Jesus as the new Moses pronouncing covenant curses and future hope.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 24 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 24, 'kids', 1, 'What did Jesus say would happen to the temple?', 'There shall not be left here one stone upon another, that shall not be thrown down', 'The temple would last forever', 'The temple would grow even bigger', 'Nothing would ever change', 'a', 'Matthew 24:2 — "And Jesus said unto them, See ye not all these things? verily I say unto you, There shall not be left here one stone upon another, that shall not be thrown down."'),
('Matthew', 24, 'kids', 2, 'What did Jesus say about the day and hour of His return?', 'No one knows the day or hour — not the angels, not even the Son — only the Father', 'Everyone will know exactly when He returns', 'He told His disciples the exact date', 'He will never return', 'a', 'Matthew 24:36 — "But of that day and hour knoweth no man, no, not the angels of heaven, but my Father only."'),
('Matthew', 24, 'kids', 3, 'What did Jesus say about being ready for His coming?', 'Watch therefore: for ye know not what hour your Lord doth come — always be ready', 'You can prepare later', 'There is no need to watch', 'Only adults need to be ready', 'a', 'Matthew 24:42 — "Watch therefore: for ye know not what hour your Lord doth come."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 24, 'teens', 1, 'What warning did Jesus give about false Christs in the last days?', 'Many shall come in my name, saying, I am Christ; and shall deceive many. If anyone says "Lo, here is Christ," do not believe it', 'There will be no false teachers', 'Everyone who claims to be Christ should be followed', 'False Christs will be easy to identify', 'a', 'Matthew 24:5,23 — "For many shall come in my name, saying, I am Christ; and shall deceive many... Then if any man shall say unto you, Lo, here is Christ, or there; believe it not."'),
('Matthew', 24, 'teens', 2, 'What did Jesus say about the gospel being preached before the end comes?', 'This gospel of the kingdom shall be preached in all the world for a witness unto all nations; and then shall the end come', 'The gospel is only for Israel', 'The end will come before the gospel spreads', 'Only a few people need to hear the gospel', 'a', 'Matthew 24:14 — "And this gospel of the kingdom shall be preached in all the world for a witness unto all nations; and then shall the end come."'),
('Matthew', 24, 'teens', 3, 'How did Jesus describe His second coming?', 'As the lightning cometh out of the east, and shineth even unto the west; so shall also the coming of the Son of man be — it will be visible, sudden, and unmistakable', 'He will come secretly and only a few will know', 'He will come slowly over many years', 'He will only come in spirit, not physically', 'a', 'Matthew 24:27 — "For as the lightning cometh out of the east, and shineth even unto the west; so shall also the coming of the Son of man be."'),
('Matthew', 24, 'teens', 4, 'What did Jesus say the days before His coming would be like?', 'As the days of Noah were — people were eating, drinking, marrying, and giving in marriage, not expecting the flood until it came and took them all away', 'Everyone will be praying and fasting', 'The whole world will be at peace', 'Everyone will know exactly when He comes', 'a', 'Matthew 24:37-39 — "But as the days of Noe were, so shall also the coming of the Son of man be. For as in the days that were before the flood they were eating and drinking, marrying and giving in marriage, until the day that Noe entered into the ark."'),
('Matthew', 24, 'teens', 5, 'What parable did Jesus tell about a faithful and wise servant?', 'A faithful and wise servant is one whom his master has put in charge of his household to give them food in due season — blessed is that servant who is found doing his job when the master returns', 'A servant who hides and waits for the master', 'A servant who quits when the master leaves', 'A servant who only works when watched', 'a', 'Matthew 24:45-46 — "Who then is a faithful and wise servant, whom his lord hath made ruler over his household, to give them meat in due season? Blessed is that servant, whom his lord when he cometh shall find so doing."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 24, 'adults', 1, 'How does the Olivet Discourse address both the destruction of Jerusalem (AD 70) and the Second Coming?', 'Jesus'' disciples asked about the temple''s destruction and the end of the age as if they were the same event. Jesus'' answer weaves together both horizons: verses 4-35 primarily address the fall of Jerusalem (near fulfilment), while verses 36-51 shift to the unknown timing of the Second Coming (far fulfilment). The phrase "but of that day and hour knoweth no man" (v.36) marks the transition', 'The entire discourse is about AD 70 only', 'The entire discourse is about the Second Coming only', 'There is no structure to the discourse', 'a', 'Matthew 24:1-51 — The disciples'' compound question (v.3: "when?" + "what sign of thy coming and the end?") receives a layered answer. Signs of the temple''s fall (vv.15-28) were fulfilled in AD 70. The unknown day/hour (v.36) and sudden arrival (vv.37-44) apply to the still-future return. Both horizons overlap in prophetic telescoping.'),
('Matthew', 24, 'adults', 2, 'What is the "abomination of desolation" (24:15) and how was it fulfilled?', 'Daniel 9:27 and 11:31 prophesied a sacrilege that desecrates the holy place. In the near fulfilment, this was the Roman army surrounding Jerusalem (Luke 21:20) and ultimately the Roman standards/idols in the temple area during the siege of AD 70. Jesus commands those who see this to flee immediately — which the early Christians did, escaping to Pella', 'It refers only to a future event', 'It was fulfilled by Antiochus Epiphanes and never again', 'The phrase has no identifiable referent', 'a', 'Matthew 24:15 — "When ye therefore shall see the abomination of desolation, spoken of by Daniel the prophet, stand in the holy place." Daniel''s prophecy had a partial fulfilment in 167 BC (Antiochus Epiphanes) and a primary fulfilment in AD 70 (Roman destruction). A possible future fulfilment remains debated.'),
('Matthew', 24, 'adults', 3, 'What does "this generation shall not pass, till all these things be fulfilled" (24:34) mean?', 'Most likely, "this generation" refers to the generation alive during Jesus'' ministry that would witness the fall of Jerusalem in AD 70 — all the signs described (vv.4-28) were fulfilled within approximately forty years. The second coming discourse (vv.36-51) extends beyond "this generation" to an unknown future date', 'Jesus was wrong about the timing', 'Generation means "race" (the Jewish people)', 'It refers to the final generation before the Second Coming', 'a', 'Matthew 24:34 — "This generation shall not pass, till all these things be fulfilled." The most natural reading: the generation addressed (c. AD 30) would see the fall of Jerusalem (AD 70). "These things" (tauta panta) refers to the preceding signs, not the actual parousia (v.36''s "that day and hour" remains unknown).'),
('Matthew', 24, 'adults', 4, 'What does the comparison of Jesus'' coming to lightning (24:27) teach about the nature of the Second Coming?', 'The lightning metaphor teaches three things: (1) visibility — lightning is seen by everyone; (2) suddenness — it appears instantaneously; (3) unmistakability — no one can miss it or misidentify it. This refutes any claim of a secret coming: the parousia will be public, instantaneous, and universally visible — the opposite of the false Christs described in vv.23-26', 'The coming might be secret and local', 'Lightning symbolises God''s anger', 'The metaphor is purely decorative', 'a', 'Matthew 24:27 — "For as the lightning cometh out of the east, and shineth even unto the west." Lightning spans the entire sky — the parousia will be equally comprehensive and impossible to miss. This directly counters false claims like "He is in the desert" or "in the secret chambers" (v.26). The real Christ needs no announcement.'),
('Matthew', 24, 'adults', 5, 'What does the Noah comparison (24:37-39) warn about?', 'The danger is not exceptional wickedness (the Genesis 6 sins are not mentioned) but normal life without eschatological awareness — "eating and drinking, marrying" represent routine existence. The judgment catches people not in the act of sinning but in the state of unconcern. The warning is against normalcy without readiness, not against ordinary activities', 'Jesus condemns eating and drinking', 'Noah''s generation was unusually wicked and the comparison is about sin', 'Marriage is wrong in the last days', 'a', 'Matthew 24:38-39 — "For as in the days that were before the flood they were eating and drinking, marrying and giving in marriage, until the day that Noe entered into the ark, And knew not until the flood came." The key phrase is "knew not" — oblivious normalcy. Life goes on; the unprepared are caught unaware. Readiness, not asceticism, is the point.'),
('Matthew', 24, 'adults', 6, 'What does the faithful vs. evil servant parable (24:45-51) teach about pastoral responsibility?', 'Leaders are stewards who will be evaluated by how they served those under their care during the master''s absence. The faithful servant provides "meat in due season" (consistent spiritual nourishment). The evil servant exploits the master''s delay — beating fellow servants and self-indulging. The parable warns church leaders that Christ''s return will expose how they exercised their authority', 'The parable is about household management only', 'Church leaders are exempt from this judgment', 'The evil servant represents non-Christians only', 'a', 'Matthew 24:45-51 — The evil servant reasons: "My lord delayeth his coming" (v.48) — perceived delay leads to abuse of power and self-indulgence. The master returns unexpectedly and cuts the servant asunder (dichotomeo — severe judgment). Delay is a test of faithfulness: true stewards serve consistently whether the master is present or absent.'),
('Matthew', 24, 'adults', 7, 'How does "heaven and earth shall pass away, but my words shall not pass away" (24:35) establish the authority of Jesus'' teaching?', 'Jesus claims His words are more permanent than the physical universe — an authority claim only God can make (cf. Isaiah 40:8 "the word of our God shall stand for ever"). This statement, placed between the prophecies and the readiness parables, guarantees that every word of the Olivet Discourse will be fulfilled, grounding eschatological hope in Christ''s trustworthy word', 'Jesus was speaking metaphorically about His influence', 'Only some of His words will endure', 'This was a standard rabbinic saying', 'a', 'Matthew 24:35 — "Heaven and earth shall pass away, but my words shall not pass away." This echoes Isaiah 40:8 and Psalm 102:26 (creation perishes but God endures). By applying this divine attribute to His own words, Jesus claims equality with God — His words share God''s eternal nature.'),
('Matthew', 24, 'adults', 8, 'What is the purpose of the Olivet Discourse as a whole — is it a timeline or a call to action?', 'While the discourse contains prophetic elements, its primary purpose is pastoral, not predictive. Every section ends with an imperative: "take heed" (v.4), "be not troubled" (v.6), "pray" (v.20), "believe it not" (v.23), "watch" (v.42), "be ready" (v.44). Jesus is not providing a prophetic calendar but equipping disciples to live faithfully between His ascension and return', 'The discourse provides an exact end-times calendar', 'It is purely historical with no future application', 'The imperatives are secondary to the predictions', 'a', 'Matthew 24 — The Olivet Discourse is dominated by imperatives: watch, pray, be ready, do not be deceived. The "when" remains deliberately unknown (v.36), forcing perpetual readiness. Jesus replaces predictive curiosity with ethical urgency: the right response to eschatology is not calculation but faithfulness.');
